article.headline: Wildcats' 26-4 run the turning point
article.story:
LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Laurie Koehn scored 22 points for No. 17
Kansas State, which shot 58 percent and rode a 26-4 surge to a
94-69 victory Wednesday night over Nebraska.

Kansas State (19-6, 10-4 Big 12) trailed 19-17 after Nebraska's
Jina Johansen hit a jumper with 9:39 remaining. But Nebraska
(16-10, 8-6) made just two more baskets the rest of the half.

Kansas State took a 31-19 lead on Koehn's 3-pointer with 3:39
left that ended a 14-0 run. After trading baskets with the
Cornhuskers, the Wildcats ended the half with a 10-0 run capped by
another Koehn 3-pointer, and led 43-23 at the break.

The Wildcats' defense shut down Nebraska in the first half,
holding the Huskers to 38-percent shooting and forcing 14 turnovers
Kansas State milled into 19 points.

Kansas State hit 55 percent of its first-half shots and was
6-of-11 from 3-point range.

The Wildcats took a 26-point lead on Shana Wheeler's free throw
with 10:19 remaining. Nebraska rallied as LaToya Howell scored five
points in a 12-0 Husker spurt that cut the lead to 65-51 on Jelena
Spiric's putback jumper in the paint with 8:17 left.

A Koehn 3-pointer ended the Nebraska run, and Kansas State added
another pair of baskets to open the lead to 21 and put the game
away.

Claire Coggins and Kendra Wecker added 18 points each for the
Wildcats.

Kiera Hardy, who sat out the final 8:57 of the first half in
foul trouble, had 21 points to lead Nebraska.
